What are Neurovascular Embolization Coils?
Neurovascular embolization coils are minimally invasive medical implants designed to treat abnormal blood vessels in the brain, particularly intracranial aneurysms and arteriovenous malformations (AVMs). These devices, typically crafted from biocompatible materials like platinum or platinum-tungsten alloys, promote thrombosis within targeted vessels, effectively blocking blood flow to prevent rupture or further expansion. Deployed via catheters during endovascular procedures, they represent a cornerstone of modern neurointerventional care, offering patients a less invasive alternative to traditional open surgery.
The coils function by creating a mechanical barrier that encourages natural clotting processes, with recent technological advancements introducing bioactive and hydrogel-coated variants that enhance healing and reduce recurrence rates. While the market growth appears modest compared to other medical device segments, it remains stable due to the life-saving nature of these interventions and continuous innovation in coil design and deployment systems.
